      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark solutions or manufactured solution tests must confirm correct numerical implementation at Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed using the method of manufactured solutions for the Navier-Stokes solver. Results confirmed second-order spatial convergence consistent with the discretization scheme, satisfying Gradation 2 criteria."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Systematic mesh refinement study with Richardson extrapolation or GCI analysis must demonstrate discretization error below 5% for QoI at Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted (3.2M, 8.7M, and 22.1M cells). GCI analysis yielded a fine-grid GCI of 1.8% for the hemolysis index QoI, exceeding the Gradation 2 threshold and qualifying for Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions must be documented and replicated in the simulation within acceptable tolerances at Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Inlet flow rates, rotational speeds, and fluid properties used in the CFD model were matched to the experimental test conditions within ±2%, with full traceability to calibrated instrumentation records."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (e.g., E% or validation metric) must be computed and documented at Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were compared against published FDA experimental data across all 5 operating points. Mean absolute error was 8.3%, within the acceptance band for Gradation 2 at this model risk level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoIs used in validation must be directly traceable to the COU decision quantities at Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH), which directly maps to the relative hemolysis index (RH) acceptance criterion specified in the COU. The linkage between validation QoI and decision QoI is explicitly documented."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments must be representative of the COU operating envelope in terms of geometry, flow regime, and fluid properties at Gradation 2.",
      "rationale": "Validation was performed on the FDA benchmark centrifugal pump geometry under the same flow-speed operating points as the COU. Blood analog fluid (water-glycerin) properties were matched to within 3% of physiologic blood viscosity, confirming representativeness at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "A qualitative assessment of numerical solver error was conducted by the credibility assessment team. Iterative convergence was monitored across all simulation runs; residuals were reduced by at least six orders of magnitude in all cases, and mass imbalance was below 0.01% for every operating point. The team reviewed solver log files and confirmed that no divergence events or anomalous convergence behavior occurred during the production runs. Round-off error contributions were considered negligible given the double-precision floating-point arithmetic employed throughout. The overall assessment concludes that numerical solver error does not materially affect the hemolysis QoI predictions, and the factor is considered to contribute positively to the overall credibility conclusion. This holistic review, while not mapped to a discrete gradation level, is consistent with practices accepted at Model Risk Level 2 for Class II devices where the solver is a well-established commercial platform with an extensive validation history in cardiovascular CFD applications.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence and round-off error must be characterized and shown to be negligible relative to other error sources."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At MRL 2 for Class II, use error assessment at Gradation 1 is sufficient.",
      "rationale": "Use error was scoped to Gradation 1 per the MRL 2 requirements matrix. Simulation setup was performed by an experienced CFD engineer with documented training records; a peer review of model setup parameters was completed prior to production runs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At MRL 2, model form assessment at Gradation 1 requires identification and documentation of key modeling assumptions.",
      "rationale": "The k-omega SST turbulence model was selected based on its established performance for rotating machinery flows. The Giersiepen power-law hemolysis model was applied as the standard approach in the literature. Key assumptions (Newtonian blood analog, rigid walls, steady-state approximation at each operating point) are documented in the simulation plan."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Input parameters must be identified and nominal values documented at Gradation 1.",
      "rationale": "All model input parameters including fluid density, viscosity, pump geometry dimensions, rotational speed, and inlet boundary conditions are documented in the simulation input log with traceability to source data."
    },
